Each step below should correspond to a new C++ module (.h and .cpp), a test driver, and a compile script. The test driver for each step should just make an image of the output at "/home/w/Projects/simple-map-gen"; or more than one if warrented. Be sure that each image is given a zero-left-padded number prefix in its name so that the images sort themselves. Each tester should read a seed from a local file so that they are consistent. The goal is zero-args passed via CLI. If we at some point add a step to the middle of the process numbers will get duplicated; that is OK. Make sure each tester also times how long generator or adjuster being tested take to finish the job.

These are the steps of process 1:
 - 01. Generator: Make a continent outline with a shaper and return overlay of outline.
 - 02. Adjuster: On an all-ocean map, fill the outline with plains terrain.
 - 03. Generator: Get perlin noise. 
 - 04. Generator: Create a flood fill overlay that counts the distance to the outline limit inside of the outline.
 - 05. Generator: Make shaped outline with radial parameter at 0.00; this will give a coastaline with more interest, but no large lakes. 
 - 06. Generator: Make shaped outline with radial parameter at 0.85; this will give a faithful coastline, but many large inland lakes. (NOTE: Same class as above) 
 - 07. Adjuster: Merge the two shaped outlines; favor 0.00 near coasts, favor 0.85 centrally; add ocean, sea, and costal, but no hills or mountains.
       Not adding hills or mountains is new behavior.
 - 08. Generator: Derive river sector points and return C-array of points and IDs.
 - 09. Generator: Claim tiles for sectors and return overlay with sector owner IDs.
 - 10. Generator: Do river network formation. Return overlay of watershed IDs (and other data). 
       One innovation we want here is to randomly give differing claims per turn (1,2,3 or 4) to different claimers; we want big and small watersheds.
       Moreover, only consider about 50% of coastal sectors as coastal; this is to limit really tiny watersheds; rule is to never have a coastal sector adjacent to another. 
 - 11. Generator: Do river line overlay creation. Return river overlay and river data in struct.
 - 12. Adjustor: Grouped rivers should be adjusted on map to coastal (i.e., a lake)
 - 13. Adjustor: Inlets should be created at some percantage of the river depth. 
 - 14. Generator: Select which watershed-pair border will have mountains on them; return overlay. 
 - 15. Generator: Create an overlay that shows distance-to-river, but only over land.
 - 16. Generator: Create a dissipation overlay from watershed mountain border, but only over land.
       This is new, we want to start at some high value at the watershed border and then count down, but never go negative.  
 - 17. Adjuster: Perlin noise (from step 3) together with dissipation overlay and distance-to-river to determine where hills and mountains go.
       This is new: We want watershed mountain border to impact/add-with the perlin noise overlay to give us mountain lines. 
 - 18. Adjustor: Make sure all water 8-adjacent to land is coastal, not sea or ocean (NEW). 
 - 19. Adjustor: Make sure all water 8-adjacent to coastal is sea, not ocean (NEW).      
 - 20. Adjustor: Make sure all land on or 8-adjacent to rivers is plains, not hills or mountains (NEW).   
 - 21. Adjustor: Downgrade mountains 8-adjacent to plains to hills (NEW). 
 - 22. Generator: Generate climate overlay.  
 - 23. Generator: Reversed depth first walk from all river mouths; cull all rivers that have nothing but desert upstream.  
